            "abstractNote": "We investigated the remarkable roosting behavior of Docidocercus gigliotosi, an understory pseudophylline katydid in the lowland forests of Panama. The insects used a spiny terrestrial bromeliad, Aechmea magdalenae, as a daytime shelter and were signiﬁcantly more frequently found in those plants, which had been: (1) higher; (2) of better quality; (3) closer to ‘night time walkways’ into the canopy; and (4) showed a better central tube condition. The katydids demonstrated strong site ﬁdelity, returning to the same plants for up to 3 wk. Such a choice may provide sufﬁcient protection against some predators and serve as a suitable shelter for the offspring.",
